In a statement on Tuesday, Ghana's central bank said the placement represented continued cooperation between Ghana, the IMF and the Swiss State Secretariat for Economic Affairs. The Adviser, Leonard Chumo, began his assignment on February 6. He is expected to stay for three years and help support the bank's implementation of Pillar two and three of the Basel II and III capital frameworks, and strengthen its risk-based supervisory framework, the statement said.  --Reuters--